{"kind":"textbox","id":"sh/dg7adsji","slide":16,"name":"TextBox 14","text":"▸  clusterProfiler: gseGO(BP) + gseKEGG (rno).\n▸  Ranking statistic: DESeq2 Wald stat (descending).\n▸  Entrez de-duplicated, keeping max |stat|.\n▸  minGSSize 15 · maxGSSize 500 · BH · seed 123.\n▸  GO simplified (cutoff 0.7) to remove redundancy.\n▸  Why GSEA matters here:\n–  Acute signal is weak at single-gene level — pathway aggregation reveals the coordinated program.","textPreview":"▸  clusterProfiler: gseGO(BP) + gseKEGG (rno). | ▸  Ranking statistic: DESeq2 Wald stat (descending). | ▸  Entrez de-duplicated, keeping ...","textChars":371,"textLines":7,"bbox":[676.8,220.8,508.8,403.2]}
{"kind":"notes","id":"nt/8z25kb6x","slide":16,"text":"TIMING ~1.5 min. Two methodological pillars. On the left, differential expression: the model is replicate plus timepoint. Replicate genuinely dominates — about 52% of variance versus 34% for timepoint — so treating it as a batch term is essential. I report two significance tiers, a relaxed FDR-only cut and a strict cut that also requires a 1.5-fold change. On the right, GSEA, ranked by the Wald statistic. The key conceptual point is at the bottom: the acute signal is weak gene-by-gene, so GSEA — which aggregates across whole pathways — is where the biology becomes visible. That's why my main analysis is at the pathway level."}